  abstract = {We consider the linear model $y̌=\\̌vťa_⋆+\veǐlon$ with $\vXı\̌mathbbR^n\times p$ in the overparameterized regime $p>n$. We estimate $\vbeť⋆$ via generalized (weighted) ridge regression: $\hat\vbetǎłambda=łeft(\vX^\tv̌X+łamb\̌vSigma_wǧht)^\dagger\vX^\t\v,̌ where\̌vSigma_w$ iťhe weighting matrix. Assuming a random effects model with general data covariance $\vSigma_x$ anǎnisotropic prior on the true coefficients $\vbeta_⋆ ̌i.e., $\bbE\vbeta_⋆\ěta_⋆^̌=\vSigma_β$, wp̌rovide an exact characterization of the prediction risk $피(y-\vx^\t\hat\vbet_̌łambda)^2ǐn the proportional asymptotic limit $p/n\g̊htarrow γ ın (1,ınfty)$. Our general setup leads to a number of interesting findings. We outline precise conditions that decide the sign of the optimal setting $łambda_øpt$ for the ridge parameter $łambda$ and confirm the implicit $\ell_2$ regularization effect of overparameterization, which theoretically justifies the surprising empirical observation that $łambda_øpt$ can be \textitnegative in the overparameterized regime. We also characterize the double descent phenomenon for principal component regression (PCR) when $\vX$ and $\vbeta_\sř$ are bȟ anisotropic. Finally, we determine the optimal weighting matrix $\vSigma_w$ for both thřidgeless ($łambda\to 0$) and optimally regularized ($łambda = łambda_øpt$) case, and demonstrate the advantage of the weighted objective over standard ridge regression and PCR.},
